e.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801003309/http://www.staradvertiser.com/editorials/20100729_Piailugs_greatest_lesson_is_that_we_are_a_single_people.html|archivedate=2010-08-01|title=Piailug's greatest lesson is that we are a single people|work=Island Voices|publisher=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|access-date=|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite news|last=Downes |first=Lawrence |date=2010-07-18 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/18/opinion/18sun4.html |title=Star Man |newspaper=The New York Times |page=7 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rO3DLaY1?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/18/opinion/18sun4.html?_r=1 |archivedate=2010-07-21 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Jack-Hinton |first=Colin |date=December 1995 |title=We the Navigators: The Ancient Art Landfinding in the Pacific |journal=[[Oceania (journal)|Oceania]] |publisher=[[University of Sydney]] |volume=66 |issue=2 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Kubota |first=Gary T. |year=2007 |title=To Honor Mau: Voyage of the Hokule\u02bba through Micronesia, January 23-April 7, 2007 |publisher=Pacific Renaissance Press |isbn=978-0-9799467-0-7}}\n*{{cite news|last=Miller |first=Stephen |date=2010-07-15 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703722804575369412174085140 |title=Pacific Navigator Kept Sailing Techniques Afloat |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |page=13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108091551/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703722804575369412174085140.html |archivedate=2012-11-08 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite book|title=The History of Cartography|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=0-226-90728-7|editor1=[[David Woodward|Woodward, David]] |editor2=G. Malcolm Lewis |year=1998}}  Provides extensive explication of Carolinian navigation.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Cite video | people = [http://www.maidenvoyage.org/wayfinders-info.html Maiden Voyage Productions] | title = Polynesian seafaring - history and Hawaiian re-creation | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ghojMWv5AZA | medium = Excerpt on YouTube from VHS tape | publisher = YouTube.com | location = originally published Durham, NC | date = 1999}}\n*{{Cite video|people=Piailug, Mau|title=Grand Master Mau Piailug And His Star Compass|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OPNUJqPoKQI|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=22 July 2010}}\n*{{Cite video | people=Piailug, Mau |date=2005 |url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/natural-sciences/priority-areas/links/indigenous-education/publications/multimedia/canoe-is-the-people/ |title=The Canoe is the People: Indigenous Navigation in the Pacific| medium=CD-ROM |publisher=[[UNESCO|UNESCO LINKS]] |}}\n*{{Cite web|last=Thomas |first=Steve |url=http://digicoll.manoa.hawaii.edu/satawal/index.php?c=1 |title=Steve Thomas Traditional Micronesian Navigation Collection |publisher=University of Hawaii at Manoa, UH Manoa Library, Pacific Collection}} [http://digicoll.manoa.hawaii.edu/satawal/Pages/browseby.php?s=browse&by=category&category=45 Mau Pialug collection]\n\n{{Culture of Oceania}}\n{{Austronesian ships}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piailug, Mau}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Yap State]]\n[[Category:Federated States of Micronesia sailors]]\n[[Category:Hokulea]]\n[[Category:Navigators]]\n[[Category:Polynesian navigators]]\n[[Category:Polynesian navigation]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDavid Woodward(link changed toDavid Woodward (cartographer)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mau_Piailug"}
{"title_page": "Bert Kelly (jazz musician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Bert Kelly\n| image               = Meet Me at the Green Goose Deary.jpg\n| caption             = Bert Kelly and the members of his jazz band in 1918\n| image_size          = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1882|6|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], United States\n| death_date          = January 1968 (aged 85\u201386)\n| death_place         = [[Long Beach, New York]], United States\n| instrument          = Banjo\n| genre               = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation          = Musician, bandleader\n| years_active        = \n| label               =\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             =\n}}\n'''Bert Kelly''' (June 2, 1882 in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]] &ndash; January 1968 in [[Long Beach, New York]]) was an [[United States|American]] musician, who pioneered jazz as a [[banjo]]ist, bandleader, educator, promoter, night club owner, and night club operator. After professional stints in [[Seattle]] and [[San Francisco]], Kelly moved to [[Chicago]] in 1914 where he flourished a [[banjo]]ist, bandleader, and promoter. In 1915 \u2014 before the [[Prohibition in the United States|U.S. prohibition]] \u2014 he founded and operated a Chicago speakeasy called \"[[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Bert Kelly's Stables]],\" where patrons were introduced to early jazz.\n\n== Kelly as a musician ==\n\n=== Kelly's band ===\n'''Early [[Gig (musical performance)|gigs]]'''\n: Kelly's first professional engagement was in Seattle Washington, around 1896.  He moved to San Francisco around 1899.<ref name=\"Storyville\" /><ref name=\"Barbary Coast\" />\n\n'''San Francisco'''\n: In 1914, Kelly was in [[Art Hickman|Art Hickman's]] band playing tea dances in the Rose Room of the [[St. Francis Hotel]] in [[San Francisco]].  Kelly eventually formed his own band and moved it to Chicago in 1914.<ref name=\"Wilton\" /><ref name=\"Gioia\" />\n\n'''Chicago'''\n: Kelly's band in Chicago included notable early [[New Orleans]] jazz musicians, including [[Alcide Nunez]], [[Tom Brown (trombonist)|Tom Brown]], [[Gussie Mueller]], [[Emile Christian]], and Ragbaby Stephens.\n\n=== Early use of the word \"jazz\" ===\nKelly claimed that his band, Bert Kelly's Jazz Band, was the first to publish the word \"jazz\" in 1915.<ref name=\"jazz name\" />\n\n* In 1914, use of the word \"jass\" (forerunner to the word \"jazz\") was forbidden in mixed company in Chicago.  Just before winning the Chicago mayoral election in late 1914, [[William Hale Thompson|Bill Thompson's]] first police chief ordered [[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Bert Kelly's Stables]] \u2014 the first \"joint\" on [[Rush Street (Chicago)|Rush Street]] \u2014 to take down a painted banner advertising \"Jass Music.\"  And, public opinion approved.<ref name=\"jazz music\" />\n* In the fall of 1915, Kelly's band had been performing at the College Inn in Chicago.  Kelly was directing and playing drums, Wheeler Wadsworth ''(n\u00e9'' Frank Wheeler Wadsworth; 1889\u20131929) was on saxophone; William Ahearn was on piano, and Sam Baum was on drums.  Paraphrasing a 1919 newsprint article by a journalist who chronicled jazz, Walter J. Kingsley (1876\u20131929), the band played blues, hesitations, and quaint [[Syncopation|syncopated]] melodies, and were quite the craze in the night life of Chicago.<ref name=\"Kingsley\" /> [[Thomas Meighan]], a movie star, gave a party one night and hired the Kelly band for dance music.  The guests included [[Emmy Wehlen]], [[Julian Eltinge]], [[Jeanne Eagels]], and [[Grace George]]. [[Richard Travers]] filmed it.  In a segment showing the musicians, he inserted the caption, \"The Originators of Jazz.\"  Thereafter, Kelly's band was known as a \"jazz band.\"<ref name=\"Kingsley\" />\n* In a 1973 article, Dick Holbrook, a researcher, refuted Kelly's claim and challenged Kingsley's published account.<ref name=\"Storyville\" />\n\n== Kelly as a jazz club entrepreneur ==\n\n=== Chicago ===\nIn the early 1920s \u2014 during [[Prohibition in the United States|U.S. prohibition]] \u2014 he founded and operated a Chicago speakeasy called \"[[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Bert Kelly's Stables]],\" located at 431 [[Rush Street (Chicago)|Rush Street]], in Chicago's [[Tower Town]].  It rapidly gained regional and national popularity as one of the jazz hotspots of the 1920s.<ref name=\"U Chicago\" />\n\nThe first house band featured [[Alcide Nunez]], whose featured number \"[[Livery Stable Blues]]\" inspired the name of the venue.  Later artists at [[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Kelly's Stables]] included [[Freddie Keppard]].  The brothers [[Johnny Dodds]] and [[Baby Dodds]] were featured in the house band after their break from [[King Oliver]]'s band.\n\n=== New York ===\nKelly later opened another jazz club, [[Kelly's Stables (New York)|Kelly's Stables]], in [[New York City]], which was prominent on the [[52nd Street (Manhattan)|52nd Street]] jazz scene in the 1930s and 1940s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Wilton\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=X5LEWiomDiEC&pg=PT111 Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends],'' by David Wilton (born 1963), [[Oxford University Press]] (2009) {{OCLC|213449670}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Gioia\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=O-b1Qmta2wsC&pg=PA61 West Coast Jazz: Modern Jazz in California, 1945-1960],'' by [[Ted Gioia]], [[University of California Press]] (1998) {{OCLC|38747512}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"jazz name\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=sol334hPuRoC&pg=PA132 Jazz in Print (1856-1929): An Anthology of Selected Early Readings in Jazz],'' by [[Karl K\u00f6nig]] (1902\u20131966), [[Pendragon Press]] (2002) {{OCLC|50072182|558438519}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"jazz music\">''TV Jazz Show Stirs Memories,'' by Donald Freeman, ''[[The San Diego Union-Tribune|San Diego Union]],'' December 4, 1961, pg. 24</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kingsley\">''[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-02-09/ed-1/seq-72/#date1=1836 ''Jazz Has Remarkable History as a Fad],'' by Walter J. Kingsley (1876\u20131929), ''[[The Sun (New York)|The Sun]]'' ([[New York City]]), February 9, 1919, pg. 6</ref>\n<ref name=\"U Chicago\">[http://news.lib.uchicago.edu/blog/2012/05/30/bert-kellys-stables/ ''Bert Kelly\u2019s Stables],'' posted May 30, 2012, ''Special Collections News,'' [[The University of Chicago Library]], Retrieved 13 August 2013</ref>\n<ref name=\"Storyville\">''[https://books.google.com/books?ei=8PAgUqymKvW-4AOyroDoCA&id=yoM4AQAAIAAJ&q=bert+kelly#search_anchor Our Word Jazz],'' by Dick Holbrook, ''Storyville,'' Storyville Publications, Issue 50, pps. 46\u201358 (December 1973 \u2013 January 1974) {{ISSN|0039-2030}}</ref><ref name=\"Barbary Coast\">''Jazz on the Barbary Coast,'' by Tom Stoddard, [[Heyday Books]] (1998) {{OCLC|38239447}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelly. Bert}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American jazz bandleaders]]\n[[Category:American jazz banjoists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Bert Kelly\n| image               = Meet Me at the Green Goose Deary.jpg\n| caption             = Bert Kelly and the members of his jazz band in 1918\n| image_size          = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = \n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1882|6|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], United States\n| death_date          = January 1968 (aged 85\u201386)\n| death_place         = [[Long Beach, New York]], United States\n| instrument          = Banjo\n| genre               = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation          = Musician, bandleader\n| years_active        = \n| label               =\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             =\n}}\n'''Bert Kelly''' (June 2, 1882 in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]] &ndash; January 1968 in [[Long Beach, New York]]) was an [[United States|American]] musician, who pioneered jazz as a [[banjo]]ist, bandleader, educator, promoter, night club owner, and night club operator. After professional stints in [[Seattle]] and [[San Francisco]], Kelly moved to [[Chicago]] in 1914 where he flourished a [[banjo]]ist, bandleader, and promoter. In 1915 \u2014 before the [[Prohibition in the United States|U.S. prohibition]] \u2014 he founded and operated a Chicago speakeasy called \"[[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Bert Kelly's Stables]],\" where patrons were introduced to early jazz.\n\n== Kelly as a musician ==\n\n=== Kelly's band ===\n'''Early [[Gig (musical performance)|gigs]]'''\n: Kelly's first professional engagement was in Seattle Washington, around 1896.  He moved to San Francisco around 1899.<ref name=\"Storyville\" /><ref name=\"Barbary Coast\" />\n\n'''San Francisco'''\n: In 1914, Kelly was in [[Art Hickman|Art Hickman's]] band playing tea dances in the Rose Room of the [[St. Francis Hotel]] in [[San Francisco]].  Kelly eventually formed his own band and moved it to Chicago in 1914.<ref name=\"Wilton\" /><ref name=\"Gioia\" />\n\n'''Chicago'''\n: Kelly's band in Chicago included notable early [[New Orleans]] jazz musicians, including [[Alcide Nunez]], [[Tom Brown (trombonist)|Tom Brown]], [[Gussie Mueller]], [[Emile Christian]], and [[Ragbaby Stephens]].\n\n=== Early use of the word \"jazz\" ===\nKelly claimed that his band, Bert Kelly's Jazz Band, was the first to publish the word \"jazz\" in 1915.<ref name=\"jazz name\" />\n\n* In 1914, use of the word \"jass\" (forerunner to the word \"jazz\") was forbidden in mixed company in Chicago.  Just before winning the Chicago mayoral election in late 1914, [[William Hale Thompson|Bill Thompson's]] first police chief ordered [[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Bert Kelly's Stables]] \u2014 the first \"joint\" on [[Rush Street (Chicago)|Rush Street]] \u2014 to take down a painted banner advertising \"Jass Music.\"  And, public opinion approved.<ref name=\"jazz music\" />\n* In the fall of 1915, Kelly's band had been performing at the College Inn in Chicago.  Kelly was directing and playing drums, Wheeler Wadsworth ''(n\u00e9'' Frank Wheeler Wadsworth; 1889\u20131929) was on saxophone; William Ahearn was on piano, and Sam Baum was on drums.  Paraphrasing a 1919 newsprint article by a journalist who chronicled jazz, Walter J. Kingsley (1876\u20131929), the band played blues, hesitations, and quaint [[Syncopation|syncopated]] melodies, and were quite the craze in the night life of Chicago.<ref name=\"Kingsley\" /> [[Thomas Meighan]], a movie star, gave a party one night and hired the Kelly band for dance music.  The guests included [[Emmy Wehlen]], [[Julian Eltinge]], [[Jeanne Eagels]], and [[Grace George]]. [[Richard Travers]] filmed it.  In a segment showing the musicians, he inserted the caption, \"The Originators of Jazz.\"  Thereafter, Kelly's band was known as a \"jazz band.\"<ref name=\"Kingsley\" />\n* In a 1973 article, Dick Holbrook, a researcher, refuted Kelly's claim and challenged Kingsley's published account.<ref name=\"Storyville\" />\n\n== Kelly as a jazz club entrepreneur ==\n\n=== Chicago ===\nIn the early 1920s \u2014 during [[Prohibition in the United States|U.S. prohibition]] \u2014 he founded and operated a Chicago speakeasy called \"[[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Bert Kelly's Stables]],\" located at 431 [[Rush Street (Chicago)|Rush Street]], in Chicago's [[Tower Town]].  It rapidly gained regional and national popularity as one of the jazz hotspots of the 1920s.<ref name=\"U Chicago\" />\n\nThe first house band featured [[Alcide Nunez]], whose featured number \"[[Livery Stable Blues]]\" inspired the name of the venue.  Later artists at [[Kelly's Stables (Chicago)|Kelly's Stables]] included [[Freddie Keppard]].  The brothers [[Johnny Dodds]] and [[Baby Dodds]] were featured in the house band after their break from [[King Oliver]]'s band.\n\n=== New York ===\nKelly later opened another jazz club, [[Kelly's Stables (New York)|Kelly's Stables]], in [[New York City]], which was prominent on the [[52nd Street (Manhattan)|52nd Street]] jazz scene in the 1930s and 1940s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Wilton\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=X5LEWiomDiEC&pg=PT111 Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends],'' by David Wilton (born 1963), [[Oxford University Press]] (2009) {{OCLC|213449670}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Gioia\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=O-b1Qmta2wsC&pg=PA61 West Coast Jazz: Modern Jazz in California, 1945-1960],'' by [[Ted Gioia]], [[University of California Press]] (1998) {{OCLC|38747512}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"jazz name\">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=sol334hPuRoC&pg=PA132 Jazz in Print (1856-1929): An Anthology of Selected Early Readings in Jazz],'' by [[Karl K\u00f6nig]] (1902\u20131966), [[Pendragon Press]] (2002) {{OCLC|50072182|558438519}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"jazz music\">''TV Jazz Show Stirs Memories,'' by Donald Freeman, ''[[The San Diego Union-Tribune|San Diego Union]],'' December 4, 1961, pg. 24</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kingsley\">''[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-02-09/ed-1/seq-72/#date1=1836 ''Jazz Has Remarkable History as a Fad],'' by Walter J. Kingsley (1876\u20131929), ''[[The Sun (New York)|The Sun]]'' ([[New York City]]), February 9, 1919, pg. 6</ref>\n<ref name=\"U Chicago\">[http://news.lib.uchicago.edu/blog/2012/05/30/bert-kellys-stables/ ''Bert Kelly\u2019s Stables],'' posted May 30, 2012, ''Special Collections News,'' [[The University of Chicago Library]], Retrieved 13 August 2013</ref>\n<ref name=\"Storyville\">''[https://books.google.com/books?ei=8PAgUqymKvW-4AOyroDoCA&id=yoM4AQAAIAAJ&q=bert+kelly#search_anchor Our Word Jazz],'' by Dick Holbrook, ''Storyville,'' Storyville Publications, Issue 50, pps. 46\u201358 (December 1973 \u2013 January 1974) {{ISSN|0039-2030}}</ref><ref name=\"Barbary Coast\">''Jazz on the Barbary Coast,'' by Tom Stoddard, [[Heyday Books]] (1998) {{OCLC|38239447}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelly. Bert}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Cedar Rapids, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American jazz bandleaders]]\n[[Category:American jazz banjoists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Premeditated Chaos", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Ragbaby Stephensclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bert_Kelly_(jazz_musician)"}
{"title_page": "A. P. Udhayabhanu", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|K. P. Udayabhanu}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015\n}}\n'''A. P. Udayabhanu''' (1 October 1915 \u2013 15 December 1999) was an Indian freedom fighter,Political leader, journalist, writer and social activist from the State of [[Kerala]]. \nHe belonged to the famous [[Ezhava]] family, Alummoottil, in Muttom near Haripad of Central [[Travancore]], who had their family title as [[Channar (surname)|Channar]]. \nHe was a leader of the [[Indian National Congress]] and served as the KPCC President. He was elected to the [[Travancore]] Legislative Assembly twice, in 1944 and 1948, on Congress ticket. He had worked as chief-editor of many newspapers including [[Mathrubhumi]].He was a Member of the Kerala Public Service Commission from 1963 to 1969. He has also served as the Chairman of the Kerala Government Prohibition Commission responsible for the 'Udayabhanu Commission Report on Alcohol Policy', besides the Kerala Jails Reforms Committee. He was one among the founders of Alcohol & Drug Information Centre (ADIC)-India along with [[Lakshmi N. Menon]] and served as its President after the death of Mrs. Menon till 15 December 1999.  He also served as the Chair-Person of the World Wide Fund for Nature - Kerala Chapter for a long time. His articles and columns used to appear in many Malayalam periodicals and news papers on a regular basis, mostly commenting on social issues.\n\n==Contribution to Malayalam literature==\nHe is also well known for his contributions to the Malayalam literature, especially towards the genre of light essays.were simple, touching and humorous. \n\nCollection of his writings Arthavum Anarthavum, Samsarikkunna deyvam, Kochu Chakkarachi, Anayum Alpam Telungum etc helped him to gain prominence as a writer of eminence in Malayalam.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sahitya Pravarthaka|first=Sahakarana Sangham|title=Viswavijna Kosa,|publisher=National Book Stall|year=1970|isbn=|location=Kottayam|pages=582}}</ref>\n\n''Enteyum Kathayum Alpam'' is his auto biography.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe was Born on 1st October 1915, at Muttam near Haripad to Komath Kunhiraman Channar and Alummottil Narayani Channatti.\n\nAfter his schooling , he did his BA ( Bachelor of Arts) in 1936 and BL( Bachelor of Law)  from the Madras University. He had legal practice in Courts of Mavelikkara and Trivandrum.\n\nA. P. Udhayabhanu was married to [[Bharathi Udhayabhanu|Smt. Bharathi Udhayabhanu]], who was a member of the Indian Parliament (1954\u20131958, 1958\u20131964).<ref>http://164.100.47.5:8080/members/mpterms.asp?terms=2</ref> She was also a writer and her autobiographical work A\u1e6dukka\u1e37ayilninnu P\u0101rlimentileykku (\u2018From Kitchen to Parliament\u2019) won her the Kerala Sahitya Academy Award, 1960.<ref>http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/pre_member/1952_2003/b.pdf</ref> She died in 1983. The couple had 5 Children\n\n== Contribution to Politics ==\nUdayabhanu was influenced by the good deeds of his Uncle T.K. Madhavan and became a member of the Indian National Congress in 1932. Being a prolific speaker he rose to the leadership of the Party very quickly. He participated in the freedom struggle actively. He was elected to the legislative assembly in 1944 and 1948 in Congress ticket.He was the President of the Pradesh Congress committee during 1955-1956.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Ente Kathayum Alapam|publisher=DC Books|year=1998|isbn=81-7130-839-2|location=Kottayam|pages=1}}</ref>\n\n== Contribution to Journalism ==\nUdayabhanu established a Newspaper \"Prabodham\" in 1948 from Alapuzha. Afterwards he served as the Editor of  \"Deenabandhu\". He had two stints at Mathrubhumi as its resident editor. Many noteworthy editorials of Mathrubhumi during these period had its origin in him.\n\n==Awards==\n*  ''Kerala Sahithya Academy Award'' for lifetime contributions in 1933\n*  ''Swadeshabhimani'' Award for contributions to   journalism in 1933\n*  ''Pathradhipar K. Sukumaran Memorial Award'' in 1995\n*  ''C. Achyutha Menon Award''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Udayabhanu, A P}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Narayana Guru]]\n[[Category:Malayali politicians]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian editors]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|K. P. Udayabhanu}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015\n}}\n'''A. P. Udayabhanu''' (1 October 1915 \u2013 15 December 1999) was an Indian freedom fighter,Political leader, journalist, writer and social activist from the State of [[Kerala]]. \nHe belonged to the famous [[Ezhava]] family, Alummoottil, in Muttom near Haripad of Central [[Travancore]], who had their family title as [[Channar (surname)|Channar]]. \nHe was a leader of the [[Indian National Congress]] and served as the KPCC President. He was elected to the [[Travancore]] Legislative Assembly twice, in 1944 and 1948, on Congress ticket. He had worked as chief-editor of many newspapers including [[Mathrubhumi]].He was a Member of the Kerala Public Service Commission from 1963 to 1969. He has also served as the Chairman of the Kerala Government Prohibition Commission responsible for the 'Udayabhanu Commission Report on Alcohol Policy', besides the Kerala Jails Reforms Committee. He was one among the founders of Alcohol & Drug Information Centre (ADIC)-India along with [[Lakshmi N. Menon]] and served as its President after the death of Mrs. Menon till 15 December 1999.  He also served as the Chair-Person of the World Wide Fund for Nature - Kerala Chapter for a long time. His articles and columns used to appear in many Malayalam periodicals and news papers on a regular basis, mostly commenting on social issues.\n\n==Contribution to Malayalam literature==\nHe is also well known for his contributions to the Malayalam literature, especially towards the genre of light essays.were simple, touching and humorous. \n\nCollection of his writings Arthavum Anarthavum, Samsarikkunna deyvam, Kochu Chakkarachi, Anayum Alpam Telungum etc helped him to gain prominence as a writer of eminence in Malayalam.\n\n''Enteyum Kathayum Alpam'' is his auto biography.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe was Born on 1st October 1915, at Muttam near Haripad to Komath Kunhiraman Channar and Alummottil Narayani Channatti.\n\nAfter his schooling , he did his BA ( Bachelor of Arts) in 1936 and BL( Bachelor of Law)  from the Madras University. He had legal practice in Courts of Mavelikkara and Trivandrum.\n\nA. P. Udhayabhanu was married to [[Bharathi Udhayabhanu|Smt. Bharathi Udhayabhanu]], who was a member of the Indian Parliament (1954\u20131958, 1958\u20131964).<ref>http://164.100.47.5:8080/members/mpterms.asp?terms=2</ref> She was also a writer and her autobiographical work A\u1e6dukka\u1e37ayilninnu P\u0101rlimentileykku (\u2018From Kitchen to Parliament\u2019) won her the Kerala Sahitya Academy Award, 1960.<ref>http://rajyasabha.nic.in/rsnew/pre_member/1952_2003/b.pdf</ref> She died in 1983. The couple had 5 Children\n\n== Contribution to Politics ==\nUdayabhanu was influenced by the good deeds of his Uncle T.K. Madhavan and became a member of the Indian National Congress in 1932. Being a prolific speaker he rose to the leadership of the Party very quickly. He participated in the freedom struggle actively. He was elected to the legislative assembly in 1944 and 1948 in Congress ticket.He was the President of the Pradesh Congress committee during 1955-1956.\n\n== Contribution to Journalism ==\nUdayabhanu established a Newspaper \"Prabodham\" in 1948 from Alapuzha. Afterwards he served as the Editor of  \"Deenabandhu\". He had two stints at Mathrubhumi as its resident editor. Many noteworthy editorials of Mathrubhumi during these period had its origin in him.\n\n==Awards==\n*  ''Kerala Sahithya Academy Award'' for lifetime contributions in 1933\n*  ''Swadeshabhimani'' Award for contributions to   journalism in 1933\n*  ''Pathradhipar K. Sukumaran Memorial Award'' in 1995\n*  ''C. Achyutha Menon Award''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Udayabhanu, A P}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Narayana Guru]]\n[[Category:Malayali politicians]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian independence activists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian editors]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Vijmuk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._P._Udhayabhanu"}
